const description = 'Overview of property damage claim types: auto, homeowners, commercial property, and third-party liability claims.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Types of Property Damage Claims</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Auto property damage</h2><p>First-party (your collision/comprehensive coverage) or third-party (at-fault driver&rsquo;s property damage liability). Total loss vs. repair decision based on ACV vs. repair cost. Diminished value available from at-fault driver&rsquo;s insurer.</p>
  <h2>Homeowners property damage</h2><p>Covered perils (fire, windstorm, hail, theft, vandalism) vs. excluded perils (flood, earthquake). RCV vs. ACV endorsement determines payout. Public adjusters can help maximize large claims.</p>
  <h2>Commercial / business property</h2><p>Business owner&rsquo;s policy (BOP) covers building and business personal property. Business interruption coverage separately covers lost income during repairs. Equipment breakdown coverage for mechanical failures.</p>
  <h2>Third-party negligence claims</h2><p>When a third party (neighbor, contractor, driver) damages your property. No deductible; you claim directly against the at-fault party&rsquo;s liability insurance. May also seek consequential damages (loss of use, rental costs) not available in first-party insurance claims.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-property-damage-claims-work">how property damage claims work</a> and <a href="/guides/rcv-vs-acv">RCV vs. ACV</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
